	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Government support effective in expanding Dominican Republic banana sector </h1>

			
			<h4>
												23 April 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Press reports note that since 2004, banana production in the Dominican Republic has increased from 19 million bunches to nearly 34 million in 2011, an increase of 77.2%. In 2011 exports were valued at around US$200 million, with some 25,000 jobs being created directly and 300,000 indirectly.</p><p>The Dominican Republic is a leading exporter of organic bananas, with 90% of organic bananas going to European markets. According to President Leonel Fernández, in a speech to the National Assembly, government support has been critical to the development of the sector, taking the form of subsidies for tools, insecticides, land preparation and the promotion of technical innovation.</p><p>In Europe, a number of MEPs have ‘called for further clarification of how to apply safeguard clauses in trade with Central America, Colombia and Peru, so that European production, especially bananas’ is not harmed. Parliamentarians have called for a safeguard clause that is ‘effective and easy to apply’. This needs to be seen in the context of the legal requirement for Parliamentary ratification of these trade agreements under the Lisbon Treaty.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Elnuevodiario, ‘A raise in banana exports in the Dominican Republic’, 8 March 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=93791" target="_self">http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=93791</a></p><p>ABC News, ‘MEPs call for clarification of safeguards for Latin American bananas’, 7 March 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=93760" target="_self">http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=93760</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Given the importance of the organic sub-sector to Dominican Republic’s banana exports to the EU, the growing trends towards mutual recognition of organic standards could potentially provide cost advantages to some of the countries’ competitors (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/Product-differentiation/Growing-market-opportunities-for-organic-products" target="_blank">Growing market opportunities for organic products</a>’, April 2012). Costa Rica, which has a FTA in place with the EU, and India, which is at the final stages of concluding an FTA with the EU, both have organic certification regimes that are recognised by the EU. (In addition, India is the world’s largest banana producer, with just under a fifth of global production.) This reduces the costs of certification and verification for organic exporters relative to exporters from countries where no such mutual recognition of organic standards is in place. Peru, Colombia, Guatemala, Honduras, Nicaragua and Mexico are all already recognised suppliers of organic products to the US market, potentially simplifying the process of attaining equivalency agreements with the EU.</p><p>Given these factors, the government of the Dominican Republic may well need to consider strengthening the country’s overall organic certification and verification regime with a view to securing an equivalency agreement with the EU. This could help the Dominican Republic to reduce costs and maintain its competitive edge for organic banana exports. It could also strengthen opportunities for expanding exports of other organic commodities to the EU and other global markets. In the Caribbean, the Dominican Republic is the leading producer and exporter of a range of organic agricultural commodities: it is under consideration within CARIFORUM as the ‘Centre for Excellence’ for the organic agriculture industry.</p>
		</div>
		
